{"cursor":"59934","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn Zen-Buddhism, Dharma transmission' is a custom in which a person is\nestablished as a \"successor in an unbroken [[Lineage (Buddhism)|lineage]] of\nteachers and disciples, a spiritual 'bloodline' (kechimyaku'') theoretically\ntraced back to the Buddha himself.\" Haskel, 2 The\ndharma lineage reflects the importance of family-structures in ancient\nChina, and forms a symbolic and ritual recreation of this system for the\nmonastical \"family\".\n\nIn Rinzai-Zen, inka shÅmei is ideally \"the formal recognition of Zen's deepest\nrealisation\", but practically it is being used for the transmission of the \"true\nlineage\" of the masters (shike) of the training halls. There are only about\nfifty to eighty [http://archive.thebuddhadharma.com/issues/2002/winter/dictionary-\nroshi_winter02.htm Buddhadharma, Dharma Dictionary, Roshi] of such inka\nshÅmei-bearers in Japan.\n\nIn Soto-Zen, dharma transmission (shiho) provides access to only a relatively\nlow grade. It is listed as a requirement for the very lowest ecclesiastical\nstatus, that of an instructor third class ([[Zen ranks and hierarchy|santÅ\nkyÅshi]]) further training is required to become an oshÅ.\n","linknr":1390,"url":"Dharma_transmission","recorded":1362673107,"links":43,"instances":["buddhism","plant"],"pdf":["http://korat.ibc.ac.th/files/private/Zen%20Ritual%20Studies%20of%20Zen%20Buddhist%20Theory%20in%20Practice.pdf","http://korat.ibc.ac.th/files/private/Zen%20Ritual%20Studies%20of%20Zen%20Buddhist%20Theory%20in%20Practice.pdf","http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/publications/jjrs/pdf/425.pdf","http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/publications/jjrs/pdf/425.pdf","http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/CriticalZen/whose%20zen_sharf.pdf","http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/CriticalZen/whose%20zen_sharf.pdf","http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/CriticalZen/sanbokyodan%20zen.pdf","http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/CriticalZen/sanbokyodan%20zen.pdf"